---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="SMC SuperFIB" description="A distributed trading system built around one source of truth and operator clarity.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container page-hero-layout">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Trading infrastructure</div>
        <h1 class="page-title">SMC SuperFIB</h1>
        <p class="page-copy">
          SuperFIB is a distributed system that synchronises indicator logic, a PHP and WordPress API, MT5 expert advisors, and a React dashboard. The design priority is not novelty. It is keeping every part aligned around one authoritative state.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="availability-card">
        <small>Primary challenge</small>
        <strong>Cross-runtime parity</strong>
        <p>Different surfaces needed to agree on state, timing, and visibility without leaving operators to guess which layer was right.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container detail-layout">
      <div class="diagram-panel">
        <div class="diagram-frame">
          <img src="/images/diagram-system/superfib.svg" alt="SuperFIB architecture showing indicator input, a source-of-truth API, MT5 advisors, and a dashboard." />
        </div>
        <p class="diagram-caption">The API sits at the center so execution clients and the dashboard can reconcile against the same reality.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-stack">
        <div class="panel">
          <div class="panel-title">What I solved</div>
          <ul class="bullet-list">
            <li>Backend-as-source-of-truth behavior across several runtimes.</li>
            <li>Broker time normalization and nearest-minute handling to reduce jitter.</li>
            <li>Staleness gates and hold states so risky inputs could be blocked cleanly.</li>
            <li>Parity audits to catch drift between indicator output, execution state, and dashboard presentation.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container principle-grid">
      <article class="principle">
        <strong>Why the architecture mattered</strong>
        <p>Without an authoritative backend, the different clients would eventually disagree. That is unacceptable in a trading context.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="principle">
        <strong>What the user sees</strong>
        <p>The dashboard is designed to make system state understandable quickly, not just visually appealing.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="principle">
        <strong>What stays private</strong>
        <p>I can show the topology and the hardening approach without exposing trade logic, formulas, or edge thresholds.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
